Maersk Ship Management BV (hereafter referred to as MSM) is a private limited company registered in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, on 31 January 2005. It is one of the vessel management and manning arms of the AP Moller-Maersk Group, which owns a fleet of over 550 container vessels that are deployed in all seas. MSM manages about 40 and mans about 60 container vessels.

The AP Moller-Maersk Group is headed by publicly-listed AP Moller-Maersk AS. The group is involved in various activities including container shipping and related activities; tankers, offshore and other shipping activities; oil and gas activities; shipyards and other industrial activities; and retail activities. The group is said to employ more than 110,000 people in approximately 130 countries.

Maersk Ship Management BV (MSM) is responsible for the technical and crew management for over 60 container vessels of the AP Moller-Maersk fleet. We were told by the company that it manages about 40 container vessels and mans about 60. The identified fleet can be found at the end of this full report. According to Containerisation International in June 2008, based on slot capacity, Maersk Line (the trading name for the groups container business) is ranked the world's largest container carrier.

MSMs crew is recruited mainly from the UK, the Netherlands, Ukraine, Russia and the Philippines. It has a subsidiary, Maersk Crewing Ukraine, in Odessa, Ukraine and offices set up in Novorossisysk, Russia, and Manila, the Philippines. The company has staff strength of 60 in Rotterdam and a total of about 1,500 seafarers worldwide.

We understand that some of the vessels are using AmosConnect from Stratos for advanced messaging and file data transfer services onboard.

On 30 August 2006, MSM acquired all assets and liabilities of Blue Star Crewing Services BV, Rotterdam, from its affiliated company, Maersk BV (formerly known as Nedlloyd BV) through a merger. Their financial statements were consolidated as from 1 January 2006.

Looking at the ultimate parent company, AP Moller-Maersk AS is a publicly-listed company incorporated in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 16 April 1904. It is Europe's largest ship-owning and operating company, focusing mainly in the liner sector of the shipping industry, although it has interests in a very wide range of other sectors including oil and gas, tankers and offshore, shipyards, and other non-shipping activities such as supermarkets.

Maersk Ship Management BV (MSM) has little history to speak of given its short trading history since 31 January 2005 other than the acquisition of Blue Star Crewing Services BV on 30 August 2006 from Maersk BV and the subsequent change in name from Blue Star Ship Management BV to its current name.

Looking at the larger AP Moller-Maersk Group, the first company, AP Moller-Maersk AS, was founded under the name Aktieselskabet Dampskibsselskabet Svendborg in 1904 by Mr Arnold Peter Moller and his father. In 1912, the shipping company Dampskibsselskabet af 1912 AS was founded, and these two were the main companies in the group until June 2003. The group entered shipbuilding in 1917 by establishing Odense Steel Shipyard in Denmark - the latter has built a large number of ships for the AP Moller-Maersk Group over the years. In 1928, the group started a line service under the trading name Maersk Line, and also entered the tanker sector. In 1962, the group entered the oil and gas sector in Denmark and this was a very important development as the profits from this sector have been vital for the groups expansion in other sectors. In 1964, the A P Moller-Maersk Group entered what has become one of its main sectors -supermarkets.

In 1965, Mr AP Moller passed on and his son, Mr Maersk Mc-Kinney Moller, took over as head of the group. Under the latters exceptionally competent leadership, the AP Moller-Maersk Group expanded considerably.

In 1970, the group set up Maersk Air AS. In 1972, the group founded Maersk Contractors, which has developed into a large international drilling contractor. In 1993, Mr Mc-Kinney Moller stepped down as the Groups Chief Executive and remained as its Chairman until a few years ago.

In 1999, the AP Moller-Maersk Group acquired the liner firms - Safmarine Container Lines NV and Sealand Service Inc (Sealand was the worlds fourth largest liner company then). The AP Moller-Maersk Group, through its subsidiary Svitzer, acquired on 1 August 2001 the Dutch towage and salvage company Wijsmuller. In October 2001, the group acquired most of the business and assets of the American global logistics firm Distribution Services Ltd. In 2002 the group withdrew from the bulk carrier sector (it had used mainly chartered ships).

Previously a number of substantial companies in the AP Moller group were not owned by Aktieselskabet Dampskibsselskabet Svendborg or Dampskibsselskabet af 1912 AS, but it seems that in 2002 most of these companies were acquired by the two public companies. In June 2003, the two companies, both listed on the Copenhagen Stock Exchange, merged in order to simplify the group structure and Aktieselskabet Dampskibsselskabet Svendborg became the surviving company. It then changed its name to AP Moller-Maersk AS. At the same time, two partnerships which had been 50/50 owned by these two public companies, Tankers and Liners in Partnership and Oil and Gas Activity in Partnership, became inactive. These partnerships had accounted for most of the groups activities and assets.

The most important developments since then have been the sale of some non-core businesses (including aviation) and the acquisitions of Royal P&O Nedlloyd NV and most of the UK oil and gas interests of the Kerr-McGee group. In February 2006 the liner shipping division of the group changed its trading name from Maersk Sealand to Maersk Line.

As a private limited company incorporated in the Netherlands, Maersk Ship Management BV (MSM) is required to make its financials publicly available. The latest accounts published by the company are for the financial year ending 31 December 2006 (fiscal 2006). The figures are presented in Euro () and we have converted the key figures into US$ at the year-end, inter-bank exchange rate.

Playing a supporting role within the AP Moller-Maersk Group, it might be possible that MSM is not required to be a profit centre. MSM generates its revenue from vessel management and supervision fees and in 2006, 99% of this was derived from members of the AP Moller-Maersk Group. Only a mere 1% was from third party customers. Revenues stood at 5.94m (US$7.81m), a 22% increase from 2005, and net loss was at 7.18m (US$9.44m). Much of this could be attributed to the 8.23m (US$10.83m) wages and salaries expense, which were incurred due to MSMs reorganization expenses for redundant employees.

Current liabilities (24.17m; US$31.80m) outweighed current assets (14.52m; US$19.11m) translating into a working capital deficit of 9.65m (US$12.70m) and a current ratio of 0.60:1. Cash reserves were modest at 3.95m (US$5.20m). As a ship manager, fixed assets (0.71m; US$0.93m) were naturally modest. Whilst there were no long-term liabilities recorded, a provision of 0.83m (US$1.09m) was set aside and this was for restructuring expenses intended to cover the financial consequences of the redundancy of seven employees.

Shareholders equity stood at negative 9.77m (US$12.86m) attributed by the net loss of 7.18m (US$9.44m) as at 31 December 2006. With negative equity, MSM could be considered technically insolvent. However, we did not feel that this is of great concern given its supporting role played within the group.

With AP Moller-Maersk AS as the main entity of the group, it would make sense to also look at its latest consolidated financials, which are for the year ended 31 December 2007. The accounts are presented in Danish Kroner (DKK) and we have converted the key figures into US$ at the year-end, inter-bank exchange rate.

The groups turnover comes from a very diverse base including various sectors of the shipping, oil and gas and other industries. Turnover was recorded as DKK280,460m (US$55,318m) and net profits, DKK18,658m (US$3,680m). Whilst container shipping and related activities contributed 51% of the revenue, it was oil and gas activities that contributed the most to its profits at 42%.

Its 2007 balance sheet showed current assets of DKK94,015m (US$18,543m), current liabilities of DKK71,434m (US$14,090m), fixed assets of DKK233,504m (US$46,056m), non-current liabilities of DKK109,370 (US$21,572m) and total shareholders' equity of DKK146,715m (US$28,938m). Its current ratio was at a healthy 1.32:1 and gearing ratio was reasonable at 0.79:1.

The AP Moller-Maersk Group is active in a diversified number of industries hence it should be able to weather any fluctuations in individual markets. The oil and gas, offshore and retail industries continue to do well, although the shipping industry, especially that of the liner market, is not performing as well as it used to. As 99% of MSMs revenues were derived from the container division of the group, its performance was heavily dependant on that of the group and we believe that it will continue to be the case in the near future. Given the tight seafarer market now, we view MSM as an important part of the group where it need not rely on others for crewing, which can be an increasing operating cost to the group.

In June 2008, we tried to contact numerous non-marine fuels suppliers, paint suppliers and shipyards for reference and traced three paint suppliers that have dealings with Maersk Ship Management BV (MSM). All three companies said that payments were good. Exposures ranged from US$ mid-five figures to mid-six figures per month and credit limits are either US$ low-eight figures or open limit.

One non-marine fuels supplier said that it internally grouped MSM together with the Maersk AS account. The group is viewed very positively and no problems were encountered with payments.

References for the holding company, AP Moller-Maersk AS (APMM), and the group were glowing. The groups payment record is seen as first class by most suppliers and recent credit lines identified for APMM ranged from US$ low-six figures to US$ mid-eight figures.

With regard to Port State Control detentions and casualties, few such records were traced for the vessels managed by MSM from the various databases available to us and this is much better than one would expect from a fleet of this size.

Maersk Ship Management BV (MSM) is a private limited company registered in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, on 31 January 2005. It is one of the vessel management and manning arms of the AP Moller-Maersk Group and manages/mans over 60 container vessels out of about 550 operated by the group.

The AP Moller-Maersk Group is headed by publicly-listed AP Moller-Maersk AS and is involved in various activities including container shipping and related activities; tankers, offshore and other shipping activities; oil and gas activities; shipyards and other industrial activities; and retail activities. Its container business trades under the trading name of Maersk Line and it is ranked as the largest shipping line in the world (in term of slot capacity) according to Containerisation International as of June 2008.

We hold MSMs latest financial statements pertaining to the year ended 31 December 2006. They were typical of that of a ship manager, where revenue and fixed assets were modest. Whilst the company was loss-making in both 2005 and 2006, this should have little significance as the company is likely not treated as a profit centre but rather playing a supportive role for the group particularly to the container division. Examining the groups latest accounts for 2007, they presented a set of very healthy figures owing to the performing oil and gas segment. Market references gathered for MSM and the group were very positive and the suppliers seem to view the group with high regard.

Based on all information available to Lloyds MIU, we view MSM as a low risk and would suggest credit limit of up to US$ low-seven figures.

Maersk Container Industry AS (hereafter referred to as MCI) is a private limited company registered in Denmark in January 1990. Part of the huge AP Moller-Maersk group, MCI manufactures dry and reefer containers both for Maersk Line and third party clients, including other container shipping lines and equipment leasing companies.

In December 2009, Lloyd's MIU contacted the management of Maersk Container Industry AS (MCI), who were helpful and provided us with detailed information on the company's operations.

MCI, based in Tinglev, Denmark, is a manufacturer of both dry and reefer (refrigerated) containers. The company has a wholly owned manufacturing facility for dry (20ft and 40ft) containers in Dongguan, China, and a similar facility for reefer containers (mainly 40ft high cube) in Qingdao, China. The latter factory also manufactures the more innovative integrated containers, under its brand name 'Star Cool'.

MCI is believed to be wholly owned by the huge, Denmark-headquartered AP Moller-Maersk group. MCI's customer base includes not only its sister company Maersk Line, the world's largest container shipping line in terms of TEU capacity, but also third-party clients. We were informed by the MCI management that these include the global container lines Mitsui OSK Lines, NYK and Hanjin, as well as the smaller, more specialised container operators Seaboard Marine and Tropical Shipping, and a number of container leasing companies.

The MCI management also told us that the volume of containers manufactured and sold by the company has decreased significantly over the last year, in line with the downturn in the container shipping industry. The executive explained that the volume of dry containers that MCI has sold dropped from approximately 200,000TEU in 2008 to a forecast 25,000TEU for the whole of 2009. The year-on-year decrease in the sale of the more technologically advanced (and therefore higher cost) reefer containers has been less acute, falling from about 35,000TEU to 16,000TEU. The company's outlook for 2010 is more buoyant but uncertain, as at the time of writing there is still no sign of improvement for the container industry.

The MCI management added that the large sales volume reduction over the last year has resulted in a reduction in the size of the company's workforce, especially in China. Today the company employs approximately 4,100 people in total, of which about 60 are based at its Denmark headquarters.

According to Maersk Container Industry AS (MCI), the idea behind the formation of the company (in 1991) was developed by Mr Niels Peter Raun, the Technical Manager of Odense Steel Shipyard in Denmark. On his travels to Asia, Mr Raun was disappointed by the lack of quality, supply security and high price levels of the supplies to Maersk Line. On returning home, he decided that there must be a better, more cost effective and reliable way of obtaining the containers that the company needed, and MCI was born.

MCI used to manufacture its containers in Denmark, and to obtain cost savings moved the production of dry containers to China in 1999 and of reefers to China in 2006.

The most recent accounts relate to the company's fiscal year ended 31 December 2008. These are presneted in Danish Kroner (DKK), and we have converted the headline figures to US$ at the appropriate year-end, inter-bank exchange rates.

MCI's turnover would comprise income generated from the sales of the dry and reefer containers that the company manufactures in China. Between 2007 and 2008, this increased from DKK1.81bn to DKK2.19bn (US$416.93m), while the company's operating loss increased from DKK9.41m to DKK14.86m (US$2.82m). This was due to increasing costs, and also probably due to the start of the downturn in the container industry, that started in earnest during the fourth quarter of 2008. With MCI reporting a substantially reduced sales volume between 2008 and 2009, the company's turnover and profitability is expected to have deteriorated significantly this year. This is a concern, but not as much as the much greater loss suffered by Maersk Line, the much larger container shipping division of the AP Moller-Maersk group. Furthermore, MCI will be buoyed up by the wider group, which includes the more profitable oil and gas and terminal operating divisions.

At the end of 2008, MCI had fixed assets totalling DKK34.76m (US$6.59m), and no long-term debt, so there was no gearing to consider. With the nature of MCI's business, most if not all of the transactions are current items. The company's liquidity appeared healthy at end-2008: it had a current ratio of 1.52:1 and working capital totalling DKK254.30m (US$48.25m).This situation is not expected to change significantly in 2009.

In December 2009, Lloyd's MIU obtained a favourable credit reference from a supplier of compressors supplied to Maersk Container Industry AS (MCI). The supplier informed us that MCI is a good, reliable long-standing client, always paying its bills on time. No credit limit has been set, and the supplier informed us that MCI can have as much credit as it requires. The supplier's sales to MCI totalled about 1m in 2009, down from 6m in 2008, due to the economic downturn.

Our searches of shipping media sources have uncovered nothing derogatory with respect to MCI. The subject's parent company, the AP Moller-Maersk group, has a good, solid reputation in the market. MCI's sister company Maersk Line is the world's largest container shipping line, and the group also has major oil and gas, terminal operating and other divisions.

Part of the huge AP Moller-Maersk group, MCI manufactures dry and reefer containers both for Maersk Line and third party clients, including other container shipping lines and equipment leasing companies.

Between 2007 and 2008, while MCI's turnover increased it reported an increasing operating loss. On the balance sheet at the end of 2008, MCI had substantial fixed assets and no long-term debt. The company also appeared to have healthy liquidity.

We obtained a favourable credit reference on MCI from one of its major suppliers, and its parent the AP Moller-Maersk group has a good, solid reputation in the market, with sufficient funds to buoy up the loss-making MCI until the container shipping market improves.
